Ars Centurion
Registered: Mar 19, 2012Posts: 339
Posted: Fri Oct 18, 2013 10:06 am
fishsandwich wrote:The only issue with modern technology here is that it is susceptible to modern vulnerabilities. Even if we can prevent things like the weapon systems from being hacked and operated remotely, it is still vulnerable to other forms of electronic warfare. In the worst case scenario where all the advanced electronic systems go down, would the crew still be able to operate their vessel and perform their mission? Based on the heavy reliance on tech, I cannot see how they would.It's tech heavy, but also built with a military mindset: those guns have to fire unless the guns have physically ceased to exist. If the network is down, there's a local control. If the control is down, there's some cranks that will let you aim the gun manually. If the radar isn't talking to fire control, fire the missile anyway and tell the radar to stay locked on the target. The missile is smart enough on its own to find the beam and ride it to the target.In another way, it's a lot easier to defend a ship against IT warfare than a website, because the ship can and will limit and compartmentalize outside communications during combat. So it's not going to be vulnerable to hacking at the one time you need it to be. That's not even getting into the logistics of first getting past the networks the ship uses to communicate (all secured and not publicly accessible) and then figuring out a way to compromise the ship itself.
